      title: 'Patients whose blood pressure only spikes at the doctor’s office are twice as likely to die of a heart attack or other cardiac event',
      link: 'https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/white-coat-hypertension-study/?utm_campaign=rss',
      pubDate: 'Mon, 10 Jun 2019 21:00:19 +0000',
      'content:encoded': '<p>For decades, doctors have been aware of a phenomenon known as &#x201C;white coat hypertension&#x201D; &#x2014; when a patient gets higher blood pressure readings at the doctor&#x2019;s office than they do at home, perhaps because they&#x2019;re anxious in the clinic &#x2014; but previous studies have shown inconsistencies in its effects.</p>\n<p>Now, a large new <a href="http://annals.org/aim/article/doi/10.7326/M19-0223">meta-analysis</a> confirms patients with the condition are more than twice as likely to die from a cardiac event as those whose blood pressure readings are always normal.</p><p><a href="https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/white-coat-hypertension-study/?utm_campaign=rss">Read the rest&hellip;</a></p>',
      'dc:creator': 'Ruth Hailu',
      comments: 'https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/white-coat-hypertension-study/#comments',
      content: 'Don’t shrug off “white coat hypertension” — people whose blood pressure only spikes at the doctor’s office are more than twice as likely to die of a heart attack or&#8230;',
