      creator: 'Daniel Sokol',
      title: 'Opinion: Doctors: use social media with restraint',
      link: 'https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/doctors-social-media-restraint/?utm_campaign=rss',
      pubDate: 'Mon, 10 Jun 2019 08:45:13 +0000',
      'content:encoded': '<p>More than a century ago, Sir William Osler &#x2014; probably the most celebrated doctor in modern history &#x2014; gave a lecture to medical students in which he referred to doctors as belonging to <a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=4rUNAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA97&amp;lpg=PA97&amp;dq=osler+%22the+great+army+of+quiet+workers%22&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=4iokAqNcFs&amp;sig=ACfU3U16M0MemDBW5Gl9hRSYsmGA_mrP6A&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiHgNDN1tLiAhUFyFkKHbr3BTAQ6AEwAXoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&amp;q=osler%20%22the%20great%20army%20of%20quiet%20workers%22&amp;f=false">&#x201C;the great army of quiet workers&#x201D;</a> whose voices are not heard in the streets but who offer &#x201C;consolation in sorrow, need, and sickness.&#x201D; The best doctor, Osler noted, is often the one of whom the public hears the least.</p>\n<p>Nowadays, doctors are heard loud and clear by all and sundry. Social media is brimming with doctors and medical students opening their hearts, sharing their frustrations, and venting their anger.</p><p><a href="https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/doctors-social-media-restraint/?utm_campaign=rss">Read the rest&hellip;</a></p>',
      'dc:creator': 'Daniel Sokol',
      comments: 'https://www.statnews.com/2019/06/10/doctors-social-media-restraint/#comments',
      content: 'On #socialmedia, doctors bellow their discontent to the world. This may be therapeutic, but it risks undermining public confidence and damaging the nobility of the medical profession.',
